00:38:35,940 --> 00:38:38,078
Greetings, kind sir.

769
00:38:38,998 --> 00:38:40,134
Guy Abrutti?

770
00:38:40,582 --> 00:38:41,735
I need to know some things.

771
00:38:42,234 --> 00:38:45,210
Oh, did you get
this money from Monte Rucker?

772
00:38:45,687 --> 00:38:46,805
Did you, uh...

773
00:38:47,189 --> 00:38:49,957
take it in exchange
for your silence as a witness?

774
00:38:50,894 --> 00:38:52,643
Do you remember Rashard Rucker

775
00:38:52,934 --> 00:38:55,888
at the wheel of a red hummer
on the night of december 14th?

776
00:38:58,011 --> 00:39:01,083
<i>[Spoon - "I Summon You"]</i>

777
00:39:05,399 --> 00:39:07,943
<i>Remember the weight of the world</i>

778
00:39:08,033 --> 00:39:10,498
<i>It's a sound that we used to buy</i>

779
00:39:12,496 --> 00:39:14,849
<i>On cassette and 45</i>

780
00:39:17,048 --> 00:39:18,458
<i>And now this little girl</i>

781
00:39:18,524 --> 00:39:21,069
Open your mouth and you're
losing every one of those teeth.

782
00:39:28,002 --> 00:39:30,230
You got time, don't worry.

783
00:39:30,422 --> 00:39:32,182
Hey, you made it.

784
00:39:32,234 --> 00:39:35,006
You know, I read that article
in "Scientific American"

785
00:39:35,057 --> 00:39:36,920
about the pep-rally
effect and I thought,

786
00:39:36,966 --> 00:39:38,118
"hey, if it's science..."

787
00:39:38,119 --> 00:39:39,557
Hey, I told you
everything would be good.

788
00:39:44,831 --> 00:39:46,136
Hey there, Monte.

789
00:39:47,583 --> 00:39:49,235
Yeah, I don't know
how I got this thing.

790
00:39:49,304 --> 00:39:50,769
I just came across it.

791
00:39:51,990 --> 00:39:53,861
Yeah, sorry to hear about
your legal troubles,

792
00:39:53,862 --> 00:39:56,283
but that can happen
when you open your mouth.

793
00:39:57,160 --> 00:40:00,201
My advice? Keep it shut,
uncle Rucker.

794
00:40:00,265 --> 00:40:01,606
Now, if you'll excuse me,

795
00:40:01,700 --> 00:40:03,099
I've got me a pep rally.

796
00:40:05,589 --> 00:40:06,367
Now, that was good.

797
00:40:06,419 --> 00:40:07,213
Yeah.

798
00:40:08,447 --> 00:40:11,005
<i>Have you ever heard the name Curly
Moran who worked at Symbolic Motors?</i>

799
00:40:11,054 --> 00:40:12,539
My dad went there.

800
00:40:12,696 --> 00:40:15,591
That guy Curly was the only guy around
who knew how to fix my Fiat.

801
00:40:15,870 --> 00:40:18,325
And were you aware of
anything strange about the bus?

802
00:40:18,437 --> 00:40:21,425
Other than it smelled like
something gross and dead?

803
00:40:21,529 --> 00:40:23,994
That's why you didn't take
the bus home? the smell?

804
00:40:24,039 --> 00:40:25,825
Actually,
my dad told me not to.

805
00:40:25,884 --> 00:40:30,355
I mean, he must've been totally
psychic because he was like,

806
00:40:30,356 --> 00:40:31,918
<i>"don't get on the bus."</i>

807
00:40:31,997 --> 00:40:33,907
<i>And then those guys got a limo, so...</i>

808
00:40:35,266 --> 00:40:36,438
I didn't see you come in.

809
00:40:37,041 --> 00:40:39,583
Didn't I tell you to turn off the TV
if you're not watching it?

810
00:40:39,723 --> 00:40:42,439
I get lonely when you're out
with all your fancy friends

811
00:40:42,500 --> 00:40:44,202
and I'm here by myself with nothing.

812
00:40:44,644 --> 00:40:46,401
Did we win?

813
00:40:46,736 --> 00:40:52,026
Yes, thanks to Wallace Fennel's
18 points and 10 rebounds.

